./sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4448:sdp/templates/candidates/verify/v001.md:95:- Address this recurring failure mode explicitly: Ensure this path is used on both standalone and federated modes..
./sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4451:I spotted one design-gap concern: `bootstrap_identity()` is now called on startup, but the call is unparameterized (`mode` defaults to `standalone`), so first boot identity mode depends on pre-existing file; if this startup path were first-run federated, identity would not be minted as federated unless caller writes file ahead of time. I’ll include this in the verification notes.
./sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4470:No new security exposure is introduced. Identity persistence behavior is covered by existing `bootstrap_identity` tests, and startup wiring invokes `bootstrap_identity` before first-boot announcement. Identity handling remains file-based and append-only at startup.
./sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4477:- [ ] Startup identity bootstrap occurs before `FirstBootAnnouncer` in daemon, but `bootstrap_identity()` is called with default arguments and does not explicitly set mode for federated first-boot scenarios. This can mint standalone identity unless an identity file already exists. Severity: minor
./sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4483:- If federated and standalone startup are both supported, pass an explicit mode into `bootstrap_identity()` when entering those startup flows; keep the recurring hardening check for identity persistence between boots.
./sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4514:No new security exposure is introduced. Identity persistence behavior is covered by existing `bootstrap_identity` tests, and startup wiring invokes `bootstrap_identity` before first-boot announcement. Identity handling remains file-based and append-only at startup.
./sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4521:- [ ] Startup identity bootstrap occurs before `FirstBootAnnouncer` in daemon, but `bootstrap_identity()` is called with default arguments and does not explicitly set mode for federated first-boot scenarios. This can mint standalone identity unless an identity file already exists. Severity: minor
./sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4527:- If federated and standalone startup are both supported, pass an explicit mode into `bootstrap_identity()` when entering those startup flows; keep the recurring hardening check for identity persistence between boots.
./sdp/logs/Verify_T-020_20260416T043834Z_1776326247.log:4544:- Minor: `bootstrap_identity()` in startup is invoked before `FirstBootAnnouncer` but without explicit mode, so a first-run federated bootstrap can default to standalone unless identity already exists.
